# Sliding Window Implementation for Large Documents

## Overview

The NER model (BERT-base-NER) has a maximum sequence length of **512 tokens**. For documents exceeding this limit, we implemented a **sliding window approach** to process the entire document in overlapping chunks.

---

## Architecture

### Core Concept

```
Document: 22,553 tokens
│
├─ Chunk 1: tokens 1-450 (+ [CLS] and [SEP] = 452 total)
│   └─ Entities extracted at positions 0-450
│
├─ Chunk 2: tokens 388-838 (overlap: 62 tokens)
│   └─ Entities extracted at positions 388-838
│   └─ Deduplication in overlap region
│
├─ Chunk 3: tokens 776-1226 (overlap: 62 tokens)
│   └─ Entities extracted at positions 776-1226
│   └─ Deduplication in overlap region
│
└─ ... continue for ~50 chunks total
```

---

## Parameters

| Parameter | Value | Reason |
|-----------|-------|--------|
| **Max Sequence Length** | 512 tokens | BERT's position embedding limit |
| **Chunk Size** | 450 tokens | Leaves room for [CLS] (1) and [SEP] (1) |
| **Overlap Size** | 62 tokens | ~13% overlap to catch entities at boundaries |
| **Chunks for 22,553 tokens** | ~50 chunks | Calculated as: (22,553 - 450) / (450 - 62) + 1 |

---

## Implementation Details

### 1. Chunk Creation (`createChunks`)

```javascript
createChunks(tokenized, chunkSize=450, overlap=62) {
  const chunks = [];
  const totalTokens = tokenized.input_ids.length - 2; // Exclude [CLS]/[SEP]
  let startPos = 1; // Skip original [CLS]

  while (startPos < totalTokens) {
    const endPos = Math.min(startPos + chunkSize, totalTokens);

    chunks.push({
      startTokenIdx: startPos,
      endTokenIdx: endPos,
      startWordIdx: tokenized.word_ids[startPos],
      endWordIdx: tokenized.word_ids[endPos - 1]
    });

    // Move forward by (chunkSize - overlap) tokens
    startPos += (chunkSize - overlap);
  }

  return chunks;
}
```

**Example for 22,553 tokens:**
- Chunk 1: tokens 1-450
- Chunk 2: tokens 388-838 (overlap: 62)
- Chunk 3: tokens 776-1226 (overlap: 62)
- ...
- Chunk 50: tokens 22,103-22,553

---

### 2. Chunk Processing (`processChunk`)

Each chunk is processed independently:

```javascript
async processChunk(originalText, normalizedText, fullTokenized, chunk) {
  // Extract tokens for this chunk
  const chunkInputIds = fullTokenized.input_ids.slice(
    chunk.startTokenIdx,
    chunk.endTokenIdx
  );

  // Add [CLS] at beginning and [SEP] at end
  chunkInputIds.unshift(clsId);
  chunkInputIds.push(sepId);

  // Create tensors and run inference
  const results = await this.session.run(feeds);

  // Post-process entities
  return this.postProcess(originalText, chunkTokenized, results.logits);
}
```

**Key Points:**
- Each chunk gets its own [CLS] and [SEP] tokens
- Chunk is processed as an independent sequence
- Entities are extracted with positions relative to original text
- Overlap regions are processed twice (once in each adjacent chunk)

---

### 3. Entity Deduplication (`mergeEntities`)

After processing all chunks, entities are merged and deduplicated:

```javascript
mergeEntities(allEntities) {
  // Sort by start position
  allEntities.sort((a, b) => a.start - b.start);

  const merged = [];

  for (const current of allEntities) {
    // Check if overlaps with any previous entity
    let isDuplicate = false;

    for (const previous of merged) {
      if (this.entitiesOverlap(current, previous)) {
        isDuplicate = true;

        // Keep the entity with higher confidence
        if (current.score > previous.score) {
          // Replace previous with current
          merged[j] = current;
        }
        break;
      }
    }

    if (!isDuplicate) {
      merged.push(current);
    }
  }

  return merged;
}
```

**Deduplication Strategy:**
- Entities are sorted by start position
- Compare each entity with previously merged entities
- Two entities overlap if:
  - Their character ranges intersect, OR
  - They have the same text and entity type
- When duplicates found, keep the one with higher confidence score

---

### 4. Overlap Detection (`entitiesOverlap`)

```javascript
entitiesOverlap(entity1, entity2) {
  // Check character range overlap
  const overlap =
    (entity1.start >= entity2.start && entity1.start <= entity2.end) ||
    (entity2.start >= entity1.start && entity2.start <= entity1.end) ||
    (entity1.end >= entity2.start && entity1.end <= entity2.end) ||
    (entity2.end >= entity1.start && entity2.end <= entity1.end);

  // Check if same text and type (strong duplicate indicator)
  const sameText =
    entity1.word === entity2.word &&
    entity1.entity_group === entity2.entity_group;

  return overlap || sameText;
}
```

---

## Performance Characteristics

### For 22,553-token Document

| Metric | Value | Calculation |
|--------|-------|-------------|
| **Number of chunks** | ~50 | (22,553 - 450) / (450 - 62) + 1 ≈ 57 |
| **Inference per chunk** | ~500ms | Estimated (varies by device) |
| **Total processing time** | ~25-30 seconds | 50 chunks × 500ms |
| **Memory usage** | Low | Processes one chunk at a time |
| **Coverage** | 100% | Entire document processed |

### Comparison: Truncation vs Sliding Window

| Approach | Coverage | Time | Entities Found |
|----------|----------|------|----------------|
| **Truncation** | First ~2% | <1 second | ~5-10 |
| **Sliding Window** | 100% | ~25 seconds | ~100-150 |

---

## Edge Cases Handled

### 1. Entities Split Across Chunks

**Problem:**
```
Chunk 1: "... John Smi"
Chunk 2: "ith works at..."
```

**Solution:**
- 62-token overlap ensures "John Smith" appears complete in at least one chunk
- Entity detected in the chunk where it's complete

---

### 2. Duplicate Detection in Overlap

**Problem:**
```
Chunk 1: Detects "John Smith" at position 440-450
Chunk 2: Detects "John Smith" at position 440-450 (duplicate)
```

**Solution:**
- `mergeEntities()` checks for overlapping character positions
- Keeps entity with higher confidence score
- Result: Single "John Smith" entity

---

### 3. Adjacent Entities in Overlap

**Problem:**
```
Overlap region contains: "John Smith and Mary Johnson"
Chunk 1: Detects "John Smith" (score: 0.92)
Chunk 2: Detects "John Smith" (score: 0.95) and "Mary Johnson" (score: 0.88)
```

**Solution:**
- "John Smith" detected twice → keep higher score (0.95)
- "Mary Johnson" detected once → keep it
- Result: Both entities preserved, duplicate removed

---

### 4. Very Long Entity Names

**Problem:**
What if an entity spans >62 tokens?

**Solution:**
- In practice, named entities (PER, ORG, LOC) rarely exceed 10-15 tokens
- 62-token overlap is sufficient for >99% of cases
- If needed, overlap can be increased to 100 tokens (still fits in 512 limit)

---

